I’m very conflicted about this review. It was good, the flavors rocked and I enjoyed it but also there were a lot of things wrong. An extra side of rice is $4 and you get less than a half cup of rice for that? The butter paneer tasted awesome, but there was a little over a cup’s worth sent and that was $16. The paneer was way softer than I’m used to it being prepared. The naan was basically raw, we had to put it in the oven. Just like, enough was wrong with it that I may never eat here again because the prices seem unreasonable. Delivery was super fast though, and again, it tasted dope.

This place didn't disappoint. We came here on a Sunday night and found a seat pretty easily. The place is a pub but has a pretty cool vibe with an animal motif including peacocks by the bar.  We started off with the lamb dumplings and two beers. This was an order of 5 dumplings and while they were small, they were packed with flavorful lamb. Loved this for an appetizer. I ordered the Chicken tikka kati roll -was still DELICIOUS! It came with three dipping sauces that were also delicious. I would call it a modern melty burrito. We also ordered the Royale with Cheese. This was a great burger with a mayo based dipping sauce for the fries. It seems ketchup isn't standard here as we got the last of it. Our waiter was great and seemed to be able to anticipate our needs. This is a great neighborhood spot and I am sure we will be back.

If you’re looking for good authentic Indian food and drinks, look elsewhere. I felt like I was in the Panda Express of Indian “pubs”. The food was insulting, almost criminal. $5 for garlic naan and $15 for lamb curry that looked and tasted more like a rice coconut curry soup trying too hard to be edgy and not resemble or taste like the real thing. It was simply bad.  Let me not even get started on the cocktail I ordered that was 80% ice. It’s owned by a hospitality company. Gentrification at its finest.  The one star is for the awesome hospitality and staff. If I could rate this place a 0 for the insultingly bad food, I would.

The poor waiter was the only one for the whole place, it just seemed as if they were sorely understaffed from kitchen to dining room. Too bad!

The menu was small, the portions were also very small, especially for the price. The flavors in the food were fairly good, and very simple, not very spicey. The rice was unique and tasty. The naan was not puffed as proper naan should be, and tasted more like a pita bread. The beer list was very nice - 4 distinct ciders and 20 beers of good variety were available. I had been wanting to try this place for a long time, as it often came up in google searches for Indian food, whenever I was in the neighborhood. I went with some friends who like the place a lot for brunch last week. I thought it was bad- but perhaps because of my choices? It was very strange that they stopped filling our waters when we were towards the end of our meals- only to ask if we wanted more after we had been sitting and talking for a long while and all of our glasses were empty. Just an odd method of service- it wasn't like they were closing. The cocktails had a LOT of ice. I made the mistake of ordering a wrap and it was, simply inedible. There was a cheese on it another friend I was having lunch with picked off and ate his- but I couldn't even force myself to take another bite. I should have complained, but I'm frankly surprised after I took one- two bites and never touched it after and did not ask to take it home, our server never asked if something was wrong. I think that I'd give them another chance if I was in the neighborhood, and try ordering something safer. But I won't go out of my way to go there again.

Stellar Indo-Chinese / British foodie haven..  The paratha is wonderful, the Gobi Manchurian is not to be missed and the cocktail list is creative and fitting of the cuisine.   Brunch is also amazing.   The avocado mash served on fresh, warm paratha is perfectly balanced and packed with flavor.  Definitely worth multiple visits. Walked into Pub Royale on a whim on a Monday night after work. I was surprised to see the restaurant/bar full of patrons for a chilly fall evening. Lucky to grab the last seat at the bar, I settled in and began to take note of all the tasty options on the menu. But as I looked around my neighbors tables to see if I could spot any of these mouth watering culinary presentations, I began to notice a pattern. Burgers, burgers everywhere. I had stumbled into the Monday night burger special. Here's the gist. $10 got me a Royale with cheese, a sesame bun burger with cheddar, pickles and onions. No fries were included at this price, but it did include a shot of bourbon and a can of beer. The bartender offered it to me Michelada style with a mango hot sauce and lime, which I highly recommend as long as your not adverse so mild heat. Best can of Hamm's ever. My bartenders we also super attentive and helpful, offering samples of beers I hadn't heard of. I ended up sticking around for an extra pint because of them, and because my meal was such a bargin, I left them a 50% tip instead of the usual 20%. The burger was pretty good and the whole experience for a random fall Monday was definitely worth it. I didn't don't get to try any of their colonial Indian cuisine, but from what I saw, it looks like a good reason to return.

This a great place for people trying to find a unique version of Indian food! It's a combination of a British style pub with Indian cuisine. We had the Gobi Manchurian as a starter and decided to eat it with garlic naan. This was such a good decision, the naan bread fit perfectly and the two flavors blended very well! As our mains we had the chicken tikka Katti roll. It was like a butter chicken style burrito and was also delicious and a good portion size. I would definitely go again! I hated it, which bums me out because it looked like a very promising menu. I ordered the lamb kofta tonight. Rather than tasting actual meat, all I tasted was the overwhelming spicy sauce that shadowed any chance of meat flavor. It was as if the spice lid broke off while prepping and the chef just shrugged it off and served it anyway. Just an AGGRESSIVE amount of spice for a tiny lamb dish. I would advise against eating here. I only give two stars because the server was nice. Pub Royale, if you see this, please acknowledge it because I've tasted lots of authentic Indian food and this sets the bar really low. Research places like Gandhi Mahal in Minneapolis, MN, and you'll know what good Indian food is like.
